# Rememo Domain Invariants

These invariants are stricter than normal code-style rules. Do not violate them unless the user explicitly requests a domain behavior change.

## 1) Product Model

Rememo is a note-taking knowledge base with scheduled self-review support.
It is not an automatic examiner.
The system must trust the user's self-assessment and must not introduce hidden correctness scoring of the user's knowledge.

## 2) Review Eligibility

- a page may be graded at most once per calendar day
- “day” is determined by the relevant timezone logic, not naive local comparisons
- this one-review-per-day rule applies consistently across:
  - global learning session
  - scoped learning session
  - manual page review
- after a page is graded, including `Again`, it must not become eligible for another same-day grade

Forbidden:
- second same-day grading through another entry point
- separate logic paths that disagree about whether a page is reviewable today

## 3) Learning Session Snapshot Rules

- once a learning session starts, its item set is a snapshot
- the session must not silently expand after start
- edits to page content or study questions must not arbitrarily inject new items into an already started session
- if a page inside the session is deleted, it may be removed from the session rather than kept as a broken item

Forbidden:
- adding newly due items into an already started session
- session growth caused by unrelated refetches or cache effects

## 4) Queue and Ordering

- queue order is not a critical product invariant
- `Again` is a grade only; it does not automatically reinsert the same card back into the current session flow
- do not add hidden queue-manipulation behavior without explicit product approval

## 5) Global vs Scoped Learning

- scoped learning may include pages that are also part of global learning logic
- there is currently no exclusion rule preventing overlap
- do not invent hidden de-duplication between global and scoped sessions unless explicitly requested

## 6) Limits

- the current session cap is 15 items
- treat this as fixed product behavior for now
- do not make it configurable or dynamic unless explicitly requested

## 7) Note Hierarchy and Lifecycle

- notes are hierarchical and may contain child notes
- tree operations must preserve valid parent/child relationships
- drag-and-drop must not orphan nodes or corrupt ordering/placement
- soft delete sends a note to trash
- trash items may be restored before permanent deletion
- permanent deletion happens after 10 days or by explicit user action

Forbidden:
- hidden hard deletes during soft delete flow
- restore that loses hierarchy without an explicit fallback strategy
- background behavior that makes notes disappear earlier than intended

## 8) Rich Content Safety

- `rich_content` shape is currently stable and must not be changed
- there is no content versioning system in place
- any feature touching content parsing, import, export, serialization, or editor transforms must preserve the existing persisted shape

## 9) Study Questions

- study questions can be user-created or AI-generated
- learning sessions display those questions/answers as self-review material
- question generation must not overwrite or silently discard existing user content unless explicitly requested

## 10) Architecture Priority for Domain Changes

If implementation convenience conflicts with these invariants:
- preserve the invariant
- stop and explain the conflict
- do not “simplify” domain behavior by weakening product rules
